<br>
This journal was begun when you were born, my beloved daughter, for you and any others who might wish to know of my life. Necessity has kept and keeps me apart from you, but know that you are never far from my thoughts and I shall always endeavour to send you such assistance as I can as you make your own way in this world, both in material goods and in those dear friends of mine as should pass through Kelethin with the promise to look out for you. Perhaps too my words themselves may prove to provide some guidance, both in what I did right and what I have done wrong, for no life is without mistakes….<br>
<br>
I was born in Kelethin, and within an hour, my life was dedicated in service to Tunare, the mother of all. I never knew my own mother, Lexia. She died at my birth, a tragic and inexplicable event nearly unheard of among those of our blood. My father Ravenni - &quot;The Lion&quot; as he was known among the folk of Kelethin - was devastated at her loss, which left him with the care of two infants, myself and my sister, Raynn. He was reluctant to leave us, as Raynn especially reminded him of his lost Lexia, but his very strong sense of duty and his responsibilities as a ranger pulled and tore at his very soul, for he knew that in this time of epic struggles he was sorely needed elsewhere. All too soon he married the druid Varda and brought her home to us. Soon after the birth of their daughter, our half-sister Kemie, Ravenni left quite suddenly one morning, his presence urgently required overseas for some great battle with the evil forces of Innoruk. He thought us safe in our step-mother's care, but within a short time Varda, too, was gone. She had always been a strange one, and quiet. I suppose she did her best for us but she was never meant to be tied down as a mother. Still there was something very mysterious and disturbing in her disappearance, for she vanished one day with no word to anyone, leaving the three of us all alone.<br>
     Raynn as eldest refused to let anyone else step in to govern us. We had each other, and she and I had already begun our ranger training, benefiting much from the guidance and direction of Maesyn Trueshot and the others in the guild hall in Kelethin. I well remember starting out, building up my strength and weapons skills and filling out my pocketbook by tackling bats and wasps and skeletons near the ancient druid ring beneath the tree city. I remember too the first time that I died, slain ignobly by a bat, of all things, for I was weak and loth to run to the guards. The shock of dying was less than that of finding myself reborn and faced with the distasteful need to loot my own corpse, but I found that I soon adjusted to this for I was often reckless and death seemed almost to become an obligatory daily occurrence. One day Ran Sunfire chanced to speak to me when I showed up for training, and from her I learned of the rash of fires started in our beloved woods by the pixie tricksters, and arranged with her to exterminate all of them I should see. She rewarded me handsomely for pixie dust as proof of their demise, and Dill Fireshine soon had an assignment for me as well, collecting orc hatchets from pawns roaming the area, for which he gave me better weapons.<br>
     By my sixth or seventh season, I was tentatively venturing to the north of Kelethin where orcs had made an incursion into our territory from the dark depths of Crushbone. Alone, I was afraid to venture far from the path for fear I would get lost - I was still so young and easily turned around, neglecting to attend to developing my skill of sense heading. And I learned that one must sometimes turn tail and run, as shameful as it felt to do so, for at times orcs seemed to appear from nowhere and join in the defense of one of their foul brethren whom I was in the process of beating into a pulp, usually at no little cost to my own health. Soon I was invited to join a party of like-minded souls to try our battle skills on Orc Hill. Some I fought with became boon companions and friends for life; others I met once and never again. The memory of those days and nights blurs now into one long seemingly continuous battle with only the companions changing. But of course it did not happen that way. I do remember one particularly frightful night when I totally lost my bearings on the hill and fled north instead of south, only to fall to the piercing thrusts of several orc spears on the very threshhold of Crushbone. Reawakening naked as the day I was born, I was terrified, for the orcs there were much stronger and more vile than those I had been battling, and I was uncertain too about the exact location of my corpse. As I hesitated near the northern lift, a kindly wood elf druid, Trinety, took it upon herself to gift me with Spirit of Wolf. To run so swiftly was astonishing to me. With an uplift of almost pure joy I set out and very speedily found my body and retrieved my belongings. Returning to the lift I thanked the young druid profusely and asked how I might repay her, but she merely laughed cheerfully and invited me to call upon her any time I was in need.<br>
     Of more impact however, was a chance encounter one day on the very brink of Orc Hill. There a young high elf palladin named Blakeley, with little thought of his own safety, stayed for hour upon hour casting wonderous shields upon the fighters and when need arose, laying on hands to bring them back from the very brink of death.  That day shone ever glorious in my memory, for there were many more victories for good than for evil as a result of Blakeley's kindness. I know not how many times in the midst of desperate battle I looked up to see him suddenly there, and was myself strengthened or the object of his healing touch, but I was always grateful and tried to let him know it as I turned to go on fighting. In the days and weeks that followed I would often see him there, or at the lift, always helping, and within me grew a deep respect for the purity of his kindness. Few words passed between us, instead usually just a smile or wave of recognition. The feeling grew inside me that if I ever had the chance I would choose such a path of selflessly helping others, for he was truly an heroic role model....<br>
