how off then and there and spin and do mock battle with one another. They were giddy with the newness and the need to celebrate, and when I stopped to chat and share their joy, these two initiated me into the finer art of drinking. Like the silly children that we were then, we spent an hour or two drunk and levitating, leaping from the top of Kelethin to see how far we could float and laughing uproarishly at each other.<br>
     Time passed. My friends began to disappear one by one as they began their journies to other lands. Some tried to persuade me to go along with them, but I was always too afraid. I think I was with the young wizard Toralon and bard Alkusanat on Orc Hill the night Blakeley invited us to meet him inside Crushbone. The other two were eager to go, having managed to find their way there some time before, but I was quite reluctant to go where I had not been before and very nearly - albeit reluctantly - declined. Between the three of them they promised to watch out for me amidst assurances they would see I came forth safely again, and so I went along. The dark tunnel loomed so ominously, marked by Crush's evil banners… coming out into Crushbone was little better, still horribly dark and utterly confusing to eyes that had never looked upon it. I remember feeling absolutely terrified as I followed my companions to the slave cabin where Blakeley waited. We crept over a bridge past sleeping orcish guards, and over rocky ramps and down again and I was quickly lost. Blakeley had us wait beside the cabin while he snuck into the caves and tempted orc slavers out for us to surround and kill. We had his shields to help us and make us braver, and many an evil minion of Emperor Crush fell to our blades that night, the very ground beneath our feet taking on the hue of blood. When we ransacked the dead we sometimes found keys, and to our joy were able to free a number of poor elven or dwarvish slaves who had somehow fallen into Crush's wicked hands and were forced to labor in this pit of despair. When Blakeley was compelled at last to leave, we felt our youth and weekness and soon crept out the way we had come in, knowing we had little chance to stand alone against so many vile foes without him, but vowing to return.<br>
     In the days and nights that followed, Crushbone soon became familiar to me and I liked nothing more than the excitement of venturing in and stalking, alone or with others, the enemies of light and good. By then I had my own spells and delighted in them although they were so minor. Remembering so well how blessed I had felt when I was younger and received the same from such as Blakeley and Trinety, I often stopped at the starting point of the orc lift or on Orc Hill on the way, to buff and heal where and when I could or was most needed. Although sometimes these gifts were asked of me, most often they were not. For me the reward was in the joy I felt in giving, and the occasional astonished or delighted smile or stammered word of thanks. Blakeley noticed, for he was still often around, and recognized a kindred spirit. Shyly I admitted he had served as my example and that it had just seemed the right thing to do. We both thought perhaps someday such dedication to service might draw enough like-minded souls together to form our own guild, but this dream was for the distant future.<br>
     I was growing up and maturing as a fighter, and perhaps in other ways as well although I did not know it. One day when I had just visited the bank on business, I was stopped on my return to the lift by a high elf named Thaddeus who spoke to me. He asked quite courteously if he could inspect me, and I found myself granting his wish. A few moments later he presented me with gifts of earrings, rings, and a necklace, his tradeskill happening to be that of jeweler. I stood a moment, dumbstruck at this unexpected kindness, for each was imbued with magic to lend me some small increase in strength or agility or charisma. Smiling, he urged me to put them on, then asked to inspect me once again. This time beneath his admiring gaze and the honeyed words that he spoke, the inspection seemed so intimate a thing I felt almost naked, and I found myself blushing profusely. Thaddeus remained my friend for some time after, stopping by now and then to give me some new item he considered useful to me, and asking nothing in return but the chance to admire me once again wearing the jewelry he had crafted.<br>
     From that moment on I encountered more and more strangers who stopped to consider me, some asking before they took the liberty of inspection, some doing it as if it was their perfect right, and probably considering their high levels compared to mine, it was. I endured these invasions of my privacy, eyes downcast and trying not to squirm, but could not overcome the habit of blushing at this unasked for intimacy. They all gave me gifts, often a weapon or armour item superior to what I was wearing. None would accept payment, insisting they only wanted to help a young ranger starting out in life. Their collective kindness to me was well-nigh overwhelming. Among the first I encountered in this fashion was Thoran, a truly kind-hearted ranger, who gave me a Velium Morning Star one day.<br>
     I had not seen Sodak for some time when he appeared one day and asked me to go with him to Butcherblock. Already he had progressed so far as wolf-form, his rapid rise a matter to marvel at and admire. Except for a few careful trips along the pathway to Kaladim to turn in belts from the orcs of Crushbone, I was not familiar with this mountainous region, but he pled so insistently that I at last consented, to my later regret. He had some scheme in mind to attack the guards there - presumably corrupt or so I found myself hoping - and thought my small skills might be some help or that somehow he might help me advance myself just soaking up experience while he killed. I did not know what I was doing or really understand what he intended; casting one very minor spell drew the guard's attention to me and before I had a chance to catch my breath I was lying dead in unknown territory. Of course Tunare's will brought me back to life near Kelethin right away. Unhappily I made my way back to the pass into the mountains, where Sodak met me, terribly contrite, to lead me to my corpse. As soon as I had recovered my belongings, he disappeared. I had no clue where I was or how to get home, and I confess that his behavior angered me greatly and left me feeling not a little hurt. I wandered lost for quite a while before I came upon the path that would take me back to Greater Faydark, and on arrival there I fled into the woods alone, where I proceeded to get terribly drunk. This too was Sodak's fault, as he had presented me with 10 bottles of elven wine before we left Kelethin earlier, and they were too easily to hand after what followed. I downed most of them one after the other, an action I would recommend to no one. The forest vanished into lines and sharp planes and angles, I could neither stand nor sit comfortably, and had anything at all attacked me then I would have been dead and might never have come back, an object of Tunare's censure. My recovery took a long, long time that night; the shame of my behavior is with me still.<br>
     Life did not grow easier, but more difficult, and it was my male companions who made it so, or my reactions to them. Oh, Tuilere, my dear daughter, I hope and pray that you will show better sense than I did. Fight along side of them, and be friends, but do not let them lead or tempt you into foolishness! Guard your heart child, lest it bring you unhappiness and sorrow such as I have known….<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#fbe5b4><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub44.ezboard.com/beverquestersofnorrath.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=galadriaculravenni>Galadria Culravenni</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 204<br> <font color=#8B4513>(5/19/01 6:03:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub44.ezboard.com/feverquestersofnorrathfrm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=40.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Tales from a Tattered Notebook - Galadria</span><hr size=1> On reading over what I have written thus far, my darling Tuilere, I must confess somewhat wryly that my tale has taken on a tone of melancholy and melodrama that was not at all present in reality. I enjoyed my youth immensely, dear, and gloried daily that the gods had gifted me with such a blessing as life in Norrath! At times I cowered like some weakling afraid to take a single step into the unknown. Sometimes both blood and temper ran quite as hot and fiery as the color of my hair, and either my joy of life or battle-fury swept me recklessly and heedlessly into adventure of one sort or another. And you must not fault the men for paying me attention - I was undeniably a flagrant flirt! <br>
     In time I forgave Sodak for what happened in Butcherblock. He was one of the strangest of my friends and Raynn could never understand why I put up with him, but some quality within him drew me on the rare occasions that I saw him. One day he presented me with a flower of no particular use but as an object of beauty; another time his gift was a perfect pink pearl he had found that made him think of me. Meanwhile he showed no hesitation in asking to borrow money from me, sometimes almost all I had to my name. Giving in to him made no sense and yet I could not refuse, even over Raynn's strenuous objections. Often it was days before he paid me back; that he made that effort at all seemed to surprise my sister.<br>
     I had too much trouble saying no to my friends. They could ask any sacrifice of me and I would give it. I had met a young bard Yuhji by then, in the depths of Crushbone, and Alkusanat from my more youthful days had become a frequent companion. These men vied for my attention, and seemed unwilling to share me with others, insisting even on fighting as a duo rather than in groups. I spent more time in Butcherblock hunting basilisks and orcs and gnolls, and in Crushbone near the slaver tents. <br>
     One night when Alkusanat and I hunted inside Crushbone, we dived into the pool near the cabin from the cliffs above, and somehow I hit my head and was knocked unconscious. I do not know if it was my air running out or slowly bleeding to death that killed me, but I did not come out of the water alive. By the grace of Tunare restored to life, I more or less routinely set off on the path north from Kelethin and was soon back beside the pool. The first glimmer of concern came when I could not find my body. Alkusanat, with his gift of bard song, finally located it in the deepest part of the pool, but even then I could not see it and hence could do nothing to summon it closer, and my swim skill was another I had neglected. For some reason even when granted my permission, he could not drag my body either. Braving the water, I managed to touch the corpse long enough to move it slightly, but quickly became disoriented and short of air and nearly drowned again before crawling out at the end of the pool. How long we tried and failed I do not know, but my despair grew in me until in desperation I cried out in petition to the gods, not really expecting any answer. So quickly that the memory still stuns me, a calm voice whispered in my head that my body was resting safely beside the cabin. Overjoyed, I found it and knelt to loot, and as I did so the voice gently cautioned me that I was very close to the edge of the pool and should be careful not to fall in again. I never saw the young assistant guide who saw fit to answer my prayer that night, but I thanked him humbly and with reverence and never forgot his kindness in taking pity on me in my plight, nor the speed of his response. <br>
     Soon after this, I met Thoran once again. Alone for a change, I was preparing to enter Crushbone when he appeared along with his friend Wyteraven, whom he was planning to assist. They were kind enough to invite me to join them, and Thoran led the two of us, both female, to the vicinity of the slave pits beside the castle and proceeded to buff us and pull a variety of orcs nearby for us to kill. We were fine until someone released Retlon Brenclog and he appeared with his pet, and suddenly Thoran was rooted to the ground, unable to cast. To my surprise, Thoran had never before encountered Retlon and knew nothing of him. Nonetheless the three of us managed to flee to safety and return to Greater Faydark without dying, which would have proven a much more serious matter for Thoran than for either of us, and the night's adventure ended. I fear that I offended him with my laughter over the incident, for he evidently misunderstood it as criticism of his skill and prowess as a fighter. (You should know, Tuilere, that men sometimes get upset at the thought they cannot always protect the females in their company or save them from death! There are times you must just humour them and curb your tongue as there is little else a female can do when male instincts take over. I have seen this happen even to the best comrades and companions in certain situations, and even when they were well aware any fault was mine and not their own!)<br>
     Thoran was another hero of my youth, and I confess I almost worshiped him. He was and is such a fine example of the ranger, brave and true, and so genuinely kind and helpful. I kept in touch with him, and often asked him for advice which was always freely given. When I began fletching, he not only gave me tips on how to raise my skill, but would often buy supplies for me when I was too far from a shop to make the journey easily or safely. He also told me how important my magic skills were and which to practice to insure I would be ready for future spells when I obtained them, and from that date I paid much more attention to the abilities I had formerly neglected, in order to become the best ranger I could possibly be and follow in his footsteps. I blush to tell you I idolized him, and had quite a crush on him, but he was far ahead of me in level and had another life to lead at just that time.<br>
     Faydwer - in the form of Greater Faydark, Crushbone, and Butcherblock, held me until my fifteenth season. Most of my friends had long departed for distant lands by then in search of adventure, and had long been urging me to follow. As soon as I had purchased the new spells my turning earned me, Raynn and a druid of our acquaintance, one Nabosu, virtually kidnapped me and spirited me by teleport across the ocean to Antonica. Bewildered by the suddenness of the change, I followed blindly as I was led through West Commons and Kithicor Forest up to Highpass Hold, unable even to glimpse much of my surroundings or to understand the need for such haste. Nabosu quickly bound my spirit at the threshhold of the Keep so that if I should die I would be brought back there to flesh by the will of Tunare, and was gone. Raynn went about her own concerns, and I was left in these unknown surroundings with no friends nearby, more totally alone than I had ever been....<br>
