eath. Wandering around carelessly can also bring one suddenly into the lair of dangerous smugglers who will kill on sight, although others of this breed will just ignore you if you let them alone.<br>
     I spent my first day in Highpass exploring High Keep in order to familiarize myself with the amenities. There are bars, some merchants, and some guild representatives there as well as the bank. But there are also secret passageways and rooms in the upper reaches, some not safe to enter for the unwary, and in the lower parts savage Picklaw goblins have dug tunnels in an attempt to infiltrate the keep, and are a constant danger for all.<br>
     Very lonely, and very unsure of myself, I started out hating the place. I had grown accustomed to fighting solo in the depths of Crushbone, but I quickly learned that this approach was seldom possible in Highpass Hold. Safety - and success - lay in groups of at least four, and six if possible. And the narrow confines of the passages in general assured that only one group might fight at either end, at orcs or gnolls, at any given time. After letting it be known I was looking for a group, and what my class and skill level were, often I could only sit and wait for an opening. I worked on fletching to pass the time, but very quickly ran out of supplies. The nearest sources of materials were in the middle of Kithicor, which I was too scared to enter, or at the farthest point in East Karanas, a long day's journey into unfamiliar territory which had its own dangers. A time or two Thoran picked some up for me and delivered them, but always they were gone again too quickly and my hands left idle.<br>
     One of the most beautiful things about the pass is the waterfall and pool midway between the keep and the orc stronghold. Stray gnolls wander in at times and will attack you if they see you, but there are a few out of the way corners by the pool where one can stand and fish for many a long hour without interruption, and I often found peace and contentment there when nothing better offered. And I found pleasure too in beginning to learn the art of brewing, for there are many brew barrels in both keep and hold, and a variety of merchants to choose from who sell ingredients or supplies.<br>
     Fifteen seasons was almost too low for me to fight at gnolls, and certainly too low for orcs, but once I was able to join groups the experience came so fast that sixteen and seventeen came and were history almost without me becoming aware of the passage of time. I made many new friends on the ledge above the path where the gnolls appeared most frequently, some of whom have remained always dear to me. Here it was that I first met the bard Armonico, the enchanters Tisharmo and Kahrd, the rangers Layton and Corrvin, the druid Laliona, and the warrior Hoffan, and many, many others. Sometimes the gnolls came singly or in pairs and would be quickly dispatched, at other times more and more would pour in upon us and the fighting become so fast and furious we were extremely fortunate indeed if all lived through it. Some of my companions - Armonico, Tisharmo and Kahrd especially - were natural leaders, understanding the strengths and weaknesses of each of us and employing us most usefully, and under their direction I learned much of working efficiently with others, and came to appreciate the skills of other classes and how they might work best with my own particular stengths. The mix was constantly changing. Sometimes I would function as the primary tank; other times I might be the only one in the group with any heal skill and be called upon for that. Mostly of course, I was tank and caster and backup healer all in one. With practice one learns to assess the needs of the group and to do what must be done to keep all alive and do the most damage to the enemy. One of the great rewards of fighting these gnolls came the day I won the roll for my Polished Granite Tomahawk, a weapon now undervalued in the market but of inestimable value to a fighter in the teens and low twenties, at the very least.<br>
     After I hit eighteen I spent more time on the opposite end of the pass fighting orcs. I had by then become brave enough to venture twice into Kithicor during the daylight hours, sneak past the encampment of Sharlock orcs there, and go for training to the famous ranger Kithicor himself, meeting with awe the great bear that is always at his side. Fighting orcs in Highpass is a far more desperate and dangerous proposition than fighting gnolls. Their size makes the Crushbone orcs look like pygmies, and they hit far harder while there are shamans and medics and acolytes all casting at times to undo the damage swords and spells have inflicted. To die became a common occupational hazard when of a sudden two orcs became three or four or five or what seemed the whole clan at once. Tunare always saw fit to bring me back again swiftly, and as I gained in this confidence in her blessing, I came to laugh at death, spending mine freely in defense of my companions only to rise up and return and make the sacrifice again as often as it seemed necessary in the fight against the evil minions of Innoruk. One day that still sticks in my memory, I was fortunate to be part of a group mainly consisting of dwarfs, one of whom was named Mytank. We were all particularly gay that day for some reason, and filled with the joy of battle and good company. The drink flowed freely between us adding to the gaiety, and we traded languages in the brief lulls between fighting, which in spite of deaths (which included two of my own) went particularly well, with orc after orc falling beneath our shining blades. We all parted quite fondly when it was time to go, and I remember Mytank hesitating as we bowed our respect to one another. He told me that he and some others had been thinking for some time about forming a guild of like-minded companions, and that he hoped some day if such indeed came into being, a fighter such as I might consider joining them. The honour that he paid me, and the compliment in this, near overwhelmed me, but I knew that I was not yet ready to commit myself to a guild, not having found the right one to appeal to me, and besides, the guild he spoke of was a dream and might not ever see birth. We parted friends, and it was long before I saw or heard of him again….<br>
