     Back in Highpass, I found myself one day reaching the wonderful pinnacle of twenty seasons and could choose a surname. I was ready, having given much thought to this before, and called myself Cul`Ravenni - the last for my absent father, &quot;The Lion,&quot; the first meaning &quot;red&quot; or &quot;golden-red,&quot; taken from the color of my hair. A conceit perhaps, but I was pleased with it, for it seemed fitting somehow.<br>
     Soon afterwards, I felt it was high time to revisit my homeland of Greater Faydark and the tree-city of Kelethin, and so returned there for training. When I had finished honing my skills with the master, Maesyn Trueshot, he gave me a small bag and bade me fill it with certain materials - treant wood shards, a spool of dwarven wire, spider silk, and micro-servos - that could be combined in a quest for the Trueshot Bow. I was eager to acquire this fabled ranger's weapon and set out at once overseas again to Freeport. There locating one Jyle Wyndshot in the Hogcaller's Inn, I traded a number of small lanterns for the wood shards. I had heard that Trantor Everhot would only give dwarven wire to one who could provide him with a special drink called a Tumpy Tonic, and so taking ship east again, I stopped off at Sister Island to purchase a bag or two full of kiola nuts. In Kaladim in Butcherblock, I then located Tumpy Irontoe in his bar and persuaded him to make me a number of his famous beverages from the nuts. Trantor was not at his forge, but I managed to track him down and give him these and obtain the priceless wire only he seems able to make. With the wire and the wood shards, I had only two of the required four materials on Trueshot's list. The spider silks would be an easy matter to acquire either by purchase from younglings near Kelethin or by hunting down the lowly spiderlings in the forest. That left only the micro-servos, which must be obtained only from certain rogue clockworks in the Steamfont Mountains.<br>
    I had never been to Steamfont before, this odd region of steamvents and bare sharp ridges lying beyond the often dangerous lands of Lesser Faydark. Still, I had gained in skill and strength since the days of my youth, and one need not venture into the depths of Lfay to reach the pass to the gnome's land, and I found it a relatively short safe journey. Once there I found little indeed to harm me amongst the creatures that inhabit the region, and set out hunting. But this last required element - the micro-servo - proved in fact the hardest to acquire! For hours and days I hunted the clockworks - spiderlike machines that had run away from their makers and no longer obeyed them - slaying many (for they proved relatively easy to defeat) yet only one in ten proved to carry within the needed component for my quest. Sometimes friends would go with me to keep me company and help, as the task proved extremely frustrating and even boring. At last having acquired numbers that I thought enough, I returned to Kelethin and presented the full bag to Maesyn. He rewarded me with a treant staff and I was ready to try my skill at making the famous bow!<br>
     Alas, my first attempt failed. I was somewhat disappointed, but at the time I was not yet a master fletcher, having a skill of only 82 or 83, and I had come prepared with extra materials just in case, and so begged another bag of the guildmaster and tried again. Another staff… Placing it carefully in my fletching kit, again I added plane and wire and another micro-servo and tried combining them, and lo and behold! In my hands I held a Trueshot, on only my second try! Oh Tuilere, that day I was SO PROUD! Little did I know then that it would be many a long season before I would ever make another….<br>
