</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#fed995><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub44.ezboard.com/beverquestersofnorrath.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=galadriaculravenni>Galadria Culravenni</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 303<br> <font color=#8B4513>(6/8/01 4:48:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub44.ezboard.com/feverquestersofnorrathfrm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=40.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Tales from a Tattered Notebook - Galadria</span><hr size=1> We come to parts of my story now, Tuilere, that are far from easy for me to speak of or write about. I had been a flirt, and men paid me many compliments and much attention in my teens, but although I had felt affection for many of them, the strong hero-worship that I had for Thoran shielded me from any deeper involvement. He had long since married another and dropped from view and from my life, and now, at 20, I began to pay more attention to the other men I met. Often I fancied myself in love with this one or that, but always something was lacking and I found myself somewhat like a butterfly flitting to the next, with little thought or consideration for how deeply their emotions or their hearts might have been entangled. I did, in all honesty, try to warn them of what I thought to be my true nature and my inability to settle down with one, because I wanted no one to get hurt, but nonetheless some of them were. And then I met Lahja, and was swept up in one of life's grand passions - or so it seemed at the time. <br>
     We had a rather wild and tempestuous love affair that carried us to the brink of marriage, and you were the result. But something went terribly wrong, Tuilere, and the engagement ring I wore was never replaced by a wedding ring. Perhaps the tainted breath of Innoruuk fell upon him in his travels, for Lahja of a sudden was stricken with a madness of insanity that ate away at him and left only a shell of the man I thought I loved. I could not abandon him, having too much loyalty, but stayed long at his bedside nursing him until one day he simply vanished, perhaps translated by Tunare into another, happier life (or so I hoped). A mere shadow of myself, I gave your care into the hands of friends and relatives and departed Greater Faydark to wander where the wind took me, so long as it was far distant from my memories.<br>
     Much of what transpired in my next several seasons is tangled and confused or lost beyond recall. Some events are etched into my brain, but when they happened or in what order I cannot say. Some remain so dreamlike they seem almost to have happened to someone else instead, a tale heard from Raynn, or Kemie, rather than anything I took part in.…<br>
     The other day Influenced spoke of his first taste of Cazic-Thule and the thing called &quot;power-leveling,&quot; and I thought I recalled a similar experience Kemie had in a place called &quot;Sol A,&quot; or Solusek's Eye. But speaking with the druid involved in that tale just last night, I learned that it was not Kemie but I myself who went with Kylian one day to Lavastorm. He did not tell me then where we were going, but taking my hand had opened a mystic portal for us both. I stepped out into a grim and unfamiliar land, the ground jagged and barren of life, the air filled with sparks and cinders and seeming indeed to be someplace spawned in hell. I followed him blindly over and around jagged crevices and upthrust tortured ridges to find myself on the lip of a gigantic pit filled with molten red lava. Kylian dropped out of sight and I nearly panicked before he returned to coax me over the edge and down along the side to a small ledge. A tunnel lay before us, lit by a ghastly glow from both inside and out. Urging caution, he eased ahead of me past a body of some fallen warrior that nearly blocked the way.<br>
     Kylian I think had 51 or 52 seasons of experience then, and although I felt complete confidence in his awesome powers to protect me, I sensed the danger there to be very great. When he told me to move, I moved; if he said, &quot;wait,&quot; I stopped and held breathlessly still in complete obedience. Some lofty acquaintance hailed him as we rounded the last corner of the tunnel and could see the bright red glow ahead. Kylian held up his hand in abeyance and I froze, waiting. His friend was immensely curious about me, but I could hear the sneer in his voice at my lowly season and my sex, and he was cruelly blunt when he informed the druid that a high-level enchantress they both knew was somewhere within and would undoubtedly not approve! I blushed in shame even though I knew the implied relationship between Kylian and I to be false, but held my tongue. Kylian merely laughed.<br>
     He left me to scout ahead, then returning for me, led me out of the tunnel into an enormous cavern. The red glow came from a stream of lava winding below and shooting up little geysers and sparks as it flowed. We inched along a trail to the right before scrambling over the jumbled upthrust angles of rock and down a slim slanting stairway of slabs to a circular bay called &quot;The Pit&quot; in front of a massive door. There we stopped. After studying my armour for a moment or two rather thoughtfully, Kylian sat and composed himself to that inner state of communion with Tunare that allowed him to draw mana, then stood and lifted his arms and began to cast. Shield after shield he threw on me as added protection, strengthening me beyond my ability to even comprehend. After taking a few moments to recover, he departed through the door with the word that I should wait while he found something to &quot;pull&quot; for me. In a very brief time he returned followed closely by a flame goblin that was already almost half dead, and indicated I should attack it while he backed off and watched.<br>
     Even damaged as it was, the goblin was a fearsome opponent and at least my equal. I waded in with weapons flying, but managed to land only awkward blows that hardly seemed to affect it. I tried gathering my own mana and flinging off a couple of my own meager spells, but they had no affect whatsoever, and Kylian told me almost impatiently to stick to weapons skills alone and trust him to take care of the rest. At last the beast lay dead at my feet and I stood panting from the exertion and dripping sweat, grateful for the heals the druid had periodically given me that saw me through the battle. He was not entirely satisfied with the way things had gone, however, and after looking over the weapons I was using and those in my packs, he gave me a superior sword (I cannot now recall just what it was) to wield in my primary hand and had me arm myself with my PGT as secondary, and left to pull again.<br>
     This time the opponent was a cinder goblin, but I had barely begun to attack when a young goblin and a flame goblin joined the fray. I ignored them and thought to defeat the first opponent before turning to them, but as Kylian began to cast a heal my way, the flame goblin pounced on him with mad fury and the druid's health took an alarming plummet. With agonizing slowness I pulled away from the cinder and darted a blow at the nastier flame goblin, luckily landing a gratifyingly heavy slash on its arm and drawing its attention to me. My blades flashed again and again in the burning lava glow of the cavern as I whirled and spun and kicked in response to the three goblins, but my steps slowed and swinging became an agony as the wounds I took in return mounted and with them my life-blood began to flow away. But my near sacrifice succeeded in giving Kylian time to recover, and once again his heals blessed me, though we both had to sit for some time in the midst of the corpses, too spent to move or loot.<br>
     I think it was only then that Kylian realized I had never been the object of this kind of &quot;power-leveling&quot; before and truly did not know what it was that was expected of me or what I should do. I knew of course that for some reason casting almost always drew the attention of attacking mobs. In this fearsome place neither of us would survive if he, the stronger, was beset, and so keeping their attention on me, even though I was the weaker, became even more important. Free to cast, Kylian had more than enough power to keep me alive long enough for my weapons and my skill with them (which he thought admirable for one of my level) to do the rest.<br>
     With these things understood between us, Kylian led me through the door and on into the intersection of four passages. The new procedure worked well for the most part, but sometimes flame or fire goblins or higher casters which we met here were very difficult for me to taunt off of him. After a while the enchantress the acquaintance had warned him would be jealous of me joined us, but she lent herself to Kylian's scheme quite willingly and eased things by casting shields and buffs and freeing more of his mana for heals. The two of them sat on some steps almost casually while I fought and fought and fought, with hardly a minute here or there to catch my breath, until I was too weary to lift an arm and face another goblin. Somewhere in that night there was a turning for me, but any joy I might have felt in the advancing of my seasons was lost in a dim blur of sweat and pain and red shadows, a nightmare scene that now in memory has become little more than a dream…<br>
