     To my shame, I saw very little more of Thoran for some time, consumed as I became with Lahja and your birth and all that followed. But not long after Lahja's decline and disappearance when I was mindlessly occupied in Steamfont once again in search of clockworks and the elusive micro-servos with which I hoped to make a second Trueshot Bow, I beheld Thoran nearby with a young ranger Elia, whom he was helping. He introduced us, and when she left, Thoran sat with me a long while. This time it was I who suffered from a broken heart and was sorely in need of comfort and he gave it, his friendship sustaining me as mine had aided him before. He seemed indeed completely recovered, the Thoran I had once loved in my youth, and seemed to hold me in deep affection as he had not done before. Still we both recognized that if there was ever to be more than friendship between us it lay somewhere in the future, my heartache far too fresh and needing time to heal.<br>
     Day slipped into day, the hours seeming each to stretch into a lifetime. Superficially I am certain I appeared slowly to heal and regain my former self, with regard to Thoran and my other friends. But unbeknownst to them I spent long periods in solitude and isolation, meloncholy and brooding and very much alone. In Highpass Hold I spent so much time fishing that I nearly reached mastery, and my brewing skills advanced as well, as did the somewhat questionnable &quot;skill&quot; of alcohol tolerance. Wandering westward from there I ventured down to South Karana and spent time there combatting Tesch Mas gnolls with my old friend Armonico. And once I took ship with Alkusanat and some of his friends to try my luck in Kunark.<br>
     At the time - I think I was 21 then - everyone was saying that Lake of Ill Omen was &quot;the place&quot; to go for adventure. I hadn't taken too many boat rides (teleporting across between Faydwer and Antonica when I could through the grace of druid friends or kindly souls I'd come across by chance at the druid rings) and was a trifle apprehensive waiting on the docks in Butcherblock for the shuttle to take ship. Although one or two of Alku's friends had made the journey before, they offered very little information on what we should expect. A short time after zoning into Timorous Deep on the shuttles, we beheld the ship looming in the distance, a gigantic craft with soaring winglike sails that looked almost gossamer and ethereal. Hearts in our throats we leapt from the shuttle to the long descending boarding ramp and scrambled up to find ourselves on an enormous deck. I sat down immediately though other passengers wandered without fear throughout the ship exploring. The movement of the sails, beautiful to behold as they periodically rose and fell, proved the only delight of the journey, for I was swiftly seasick and had to call upon Alkusanat for his bard song of invigoration to overcome my loss of stamina. Finally the dock of Firiona Vie hove into view and we made ready to disembark. As we approached however, Alkusanat was suddenly swept off the deck and disappeared!<br>
     I heard him crying out as he frantically swam to shore, but his friends seemed not to notice his absence, or to properly appreciate the terror he might feel at finding himself separated from us and dropped into the water only to come out on land alone in a strange place not knowing where he was or should go. The poor bard seemed to have ill luck with ocean voyages, bad memories coloring his fear. Frantically I called out to the group and insisted they find him swiftly, and myself began to track him even though the place was no more known to me than it was to him. Reunited finally, one of the group led us through the fort to a bridge and bound us there. Alkusanat and I were both so shaken we could only find ourselves a camp for the night and try to recover, although the others apparently set off at once for the district of the lake.<br>
     We were alone when we awoke the next day, finding no sign of his friends in the vicinity. While we were debating what we should do, an old acquaintance, Maedowalen, passed nearby. I hailed him and he offered to guide us if we would follow, for he was on a corpse run to the Swamp of No Hope. Having no better plan we joined him. To our surprise he headed straight for the water, rather than the bridge, and dove in to swim across. Alkusanat kept up with him but I dropped far behind and was swiftly lost. At last I waded up onto the shore to find them arguing about which way to go, and Maedowalen headed off alone to the north while we attempted to find the stream or river draining from the lake, believing it to be the surest guide to us. Hideous monsters, with spiderlike bodies and human-seeming heads, barred our way, far more powerful than our skill to combat. <br>
     Alkusanat and I were some distance apart. He urged me to go ahead in the direction we thought we should go while he kept an eye on the nearest monster, and casting camouflage upon myself I crept along the shore and swam the mouth of the inlet to the northern side. A few minutes later he arrived himself, and it was only then I learned from him that my camouflage was in fact no use against these beasts and would not hide me from them! Luckily he had a song he could weave to cover both of us along with SoW, and fearfully we set off up along the waterway to the northwest. We were nearly to the zone when for some reason our invisibility failed us and one of the spider things attacked. Alku shouted for me to run but he seemed hard beset and instead I waded in weapons flying in an attempt to buy him time before disengaging the enemy and following. Alas, the delay proved more costly to me than to him and the next thing I knew I awoke naked on the bridge back in Firiona Vie fort.<br>
     Cautiously he made his way back to my corpse and at great risk to himself, dragged it all the way across the zone to the bridge so I could loot it safely. We returned into the city to try to figure out what to do, but exhausted by our ill-fated venture, soon camped. I woke late the following day. Alkusanat had put some of his hours alone meanwhile in exploring, and discovered tunnels that lay underneath the fort, one leading to the shore near where Maedowalen had led us the day before.  Inspired by this, I dug through my backpack and unearthed a crumpled somewhat dirty map that I had forgotten I even had, and studied it carefully. It looked as though by using this tunnel and hugging the rocky boundary on the west, we might find a safer and shorter path to the lake, with the added advantage of a pass to Frontier Mountains to duck into halfway along should we need refuge. Feeling we had nothing to lose but our lives once more, we soon set out. Again we saw spider creatures, some normal appearing and some with human heads, but this time we managed to reach Lake of Ill Omen without incident. <br>
     The scenery was alien, but the first creatures we met there bore at least a superficial resemblance to the lions of Antonica. These were sabertooth tigers, and together Alkusanat and I slew several before gaining enough confidence in our teamwork to search for greater foes. Ice bone skeletons, we found, hit harder than their old world counterparts, but again we managed to emerge victorious. The strangest and most dangerous of the enemies we saw that day were Sarnaks, cousins perhaps of the goblins but dark-skinned and thinner, with spiky protrusions at the joints and of truly evil nature. We stuck to the southeast shore of the lake and ventured only once south to the windmills to sell before returning gratefully to Firiona Vie fort the way we had come, knowing of no safer place to camp.<br>
     We could not make up our minds to make the fearsome journey again and things disintegrated from there. I stayed at the fort for weeks with too little to do and grew ever more lonely for familiar lands and faces. There was a fletching shop there so I could while away some of the long blank hours improving my skill but soon grew bored, and I tried fishing but found no relaxation in that pastime, for the fish I caught were strange and the setting still too alien. One day I heard a shout ring out from someone offering a teleport to West Commons and with no regrets left Kunark and Alkusanat both behind me.<br>
